          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;"><strong>🇲🇽 Mexico</strong>  Eight of the eleven justices on Mexico’s Supreme Court have <a href="https://edition.cnn.com/2024/10/31/americas/mexico-justices-resign-judicial-reform-intl-hnk/index.html" target="_blank">resigned</a> ahead of a June election mandated by a recent <a href="https://edition.cnn.com/2024/09/10/americas/mexico-judicial-reform-debate-senate-intl-latam/index.html" target="_blank">constitutional reform</a> requiring judges to be elected by popular vote. The resignations heighten tensions between the court and the ruling government, with some justices emphasizing that their departures do not imply acceptance of the reform’s constitutionality. Due to this overhaul, the court’s membership will decrease from eleven to nine justices.</p>
        </mj-text>
